05259nam a22008055i 9780812293944DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1054881011  a(OCoLC)992454015  a97808122939447 a10.9783/97808122939442doi  a(DE-B1597)481196  a(OCoLC)985342112  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0150602bisacsh1 aMartin, S. Rebecca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Art of Contact :bComparative Approaches to Greek and Phoenician Art /cS. Rebecca Martin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b38 color, 59 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 11. Culture, Contact, and Art History: Framing the Theoretical Landscape -- tChapter 2. Arts of Contact -- tChapter 3. Exceptional Greeks and Phantom Phoenicians -- tChapter 4. The Rise of Phoenicianism -- tChapter 5. Hybridity, the Middle Ground, and the “Conundrum of ‘Mixing’ ” -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAcknowl edgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe proem to Herodotus's history of the Greek-Persian wars relates the long-standing conflict between Europe and Asia from the points of view of the Greeks' chief antagonists, the Persians and Phoenicians. However humorous or fantastical these accounts may be, their stories, as voiced by a Greek, reveal a great deal about the perceived differences between Greeks and others. The conflict is framed in political, not absolute, terms correlative to historical events, not in terms of innate qualities of the participants. It is this perspective that informs the argument of The Art of Contact: Comparative Approaches to Greek and Phoenician Art.Becky Martin reconsiders works of art produced by, or thought to be produced by, Greeks and Phoenicians during the first millennium B.C., when they were in prolonged contact with one another. Although primordial narratives that emphasize an essential quality of Greek and Phoenician identities have been critiqued for decades, Martin contends that the study of ancient history has not yet effectively challenged the idea of the inevitability of the political and cultural triumph of Greece. She aims to show how the methods used to study ancient history shape perceptions of it and argues that art is especially positioned to revise conventional accountings of the history of Greek-Phoenician interaction.Examining Athenian and Tyrian coins, kouros statues and wall mosaics, as well as the familiar Alexander Sarcophagus and the sculpture known as the "Slipper Slapper," Martin questions what constituted "Greek" and "Phoenician" art and, by extension, Greek and Phoenician identity. Explicating the relationship between theory, method, and interpretation, The Art of Contact destabilizes categories such as orientalism and Hellenism and offers fresh perspectives on Greek and Phoenician art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 4aAncient Studies. 4aArchaeology. 4aArchitecture. 4aClassics. 4aFine Art. 4aGarden History. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2017z9783110547733oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229394440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293944423Coveruhttp